## 2. First-time setup — Python

### Prerequisites

- Python 3.11+ (`python --version` to check)
- Git (`git --version` to check)
- [uv](https://wolke.img.univie.ac.at/documentation/general/mkdocs/uv-cheatsheet.pdf) for package management

### Steps

```bash
# 1. Clone the repo
git clone https://github.com/apueelawekulom-lgtm/masters_thesis.git
cd masters_thesis

# 2. Create virtual environment and install all dependencies in one step
uv sync

# 3. Activate the environment
source .venv/bin/activate        # Mac / Linux
.venv\Scripts\activate           # Windows

# 4. Verify everything installed correctly
python -c "import pandas; import torch; print('Setup OK')"
```

### Register the Jupyter kernel

This makes the project environment available inside Jupyter. Do this once after setup:

```bash
python -m ipykernel install --user --name masters_thesis --display-name "Masters Thesis"
jupyter lab
```

> When opening any notebook, select the **Masters Thesis** kernel from the top-right dropdown — not the default Python 3 kernel. This ensures you use the project's exact package versions.

---

## 3. First-time setup — R

If you are using R for your analysis, follow these steps instead of (or alongside) the Python setup.

### Prerequisites

- [R](https://cran.r-project.org) installed — download from cran.r-project.org
- [RStudio Desktop](https://posit.co/download/rstudio-desktop/) installed — install R first, then RStudio
- Git configured in RStudio: `Tools → Global Options → Git/SVN` — check the Git executable is filled in

### Clone the repo in RStudio

```
File → New Project → Version Control → Git
Repository URL: https://github.com/apueelawekulom-lgtm/masters_thesis.git
```

This clones the repo and opens it as an RStudio Project — the Git panel will appear automatically in the top-right.

### Install required R packages

Run this once in the R console:

```r
install.packages(c("yaml", "here", "tidyverse", "arrow", "readr"))
```

- `yaml` — reads `paths.yaml` so you can use the shared path config
- `here` — finds the project root automatically regardless of where your script is
- `tidyverse` — data manipulation (dplyr, ggplot2 etc.)
- `arrow` — reads `.parquet` files produced by the Python chapters
- `readr` — fast CSV reading

### Add R-specific entries to .gitignore

These R files should never be committed. They are already in the `.gitignore` but check they are there:

```
.Rhistory
.RData
.Rproj.user/
*_cache/
*_files/
renv/library/
```

> **Important:** Go to `Tools → Global Options → General` and set **"Save workspace to .RData on exit"** to **Never**. The `.RData` file silently saves your entire R workspace and can be hundreds of MB.

---

## 4. What is paths.yaml and why does it exist?

`config/paths.yaml` is a plain-text file that stores every important file path in the project in one place.

### Why this matters

Without it, people write paths like this in their notebooks:

```python
# hardcoded — breaks on everyone else's machine
df = pd.read_csv("/Users/apueela/Desktop/masters_thesis/nli/data/processed/tsi_final.csv")
```

That path only works on one laptop. With `paths.yaml`, everyone writes:

```python
tsi = pd.read_csv(get("nli", "tsi_final"))
```

This works on every machine, and if you ever rename a folder you update `paths.yaml` once instead of hunting through every notebook.

### What YAML looks like

YAML is just a structured text file — it uses indentation to create hierarchy, like folders inside folders. Colons separate keys from values.

```yaml
# This is a comment in YAML

nli:                              # chapter name (top level)
  raw: nli/data/raw/              # key: value
  processed: nli/data/processed/
  tsi_final: nli/data/processed/tsi_final.csv   # a specific file

econometrics:
  raw: econometrics/data/raw/
  processed: econometrics/data/processed/
```

Reading it: `PATHS["nli"]["tsi_final"]` gives you `"nli/data/processed/tsi_final.csv"`.

### Rules for editing paths.yaml

- Use spaces for indentation, never tabs
- Keep the same structure: `chapter → key: path`
- Paths are relative to the project root — do not start them with `/`
- After editing, tell the team in Slack so everyone pulls the update

---

## 5. Using paths in Python notebooks

The `src/paths.py` file loads `paths.yaml` for you. Add these two lines at the top of every notebook:

```python
import sys
from pathlib import Path
sys.path.insert(0, str(Path("../..").resolve()))  # points to project root

from src.paths import get, ROOT, PATHS
```

Then use `get()` anywhere you need a file path:

```python
import pandas as pd

# Load TSI labels — produced by NLI chapter, used by everyone
tsi = pd.read_csv(get("nli", "tsi_final"))

# Load shared BACI data from the root data folder
baci = pd.read_parquet(ROOT / PATHS["shared"]["raw"] / "baci_semis.parquet")

# Load an econometrics panel
panel = pd.read_parquet(get("econometrics", "panel_us"))

# Save a figure to the right outputs folder
fig.savefig(get("econometrics", "figures") / "stage_composition_pre_war.pdf")
```

### Depth adjustment

The `sys.path.insert` line above assumes your notebook is two levels deep (e.g. `econometrics/notebooks/`). If it is one level deep (e.g. directly in `econometrics/`), change `"../.."` to `".."`.

---

## 6. Using paths in R scripts

The `src/paths.R` file does the same job as `src/paths.py` but for R. Source it at the top of every script or `.Rmd` file:

```r
source("../../src/paths.R")   # adjust depth if needed — see note below
```

Then use `get_path()` anywhere you need a file path:

```r
library(readr)
library(arrow)

# Load TSI labels
tsi <- read_csv(get_path("nli", "tsi_final"))

# Load an econometrics panel (parquet format)
panel <- read_parquet(get_path("econometrics", "panel_us"))

# Save a figure
ggsave(
  filename = file.path(get_path("econometrics", "figures"), "stage_composition.pdf"),
  plot = my_plot
)
```

### Depth adjustment for R

`source("../../src/paths.R")` assumes your script is two levels deep (e.g. `econometrics/notebooks/`). Adjust the number of `../` to match where your file sits:

| Script location | source() call |
|----------------|---------------|
| `econometrics/notebooks/` | `source("../../src/paths.R")` |
| `econometrics/` | `source("../src/paths.R")` |
| root level | `source("src/paths.R")` |

### R Markdown / Quarto note

Clear outputs before committing `.Rmd` and `.qmd` files — same rule as Jupyter notebooks. In RStudio: `Session → Restart R and Clear Output`, then knit fresh before committing.

---

## 7. Data conventions

> **The single most important rule: raw data is read-only. You never edit files in any `data/raw/` folder.**

### Where data lives

| Data type | Location | Notes |
|-----------|----------|-------|
| BACI trade flows (all chapters) | `data/raw/` | Shared source — download once |
| Section 301 tariff lists | `econometrics/data/raw/` | USITC concorded to HS6 |
| BIS export control lists | `econometrics/data/raw/` | 2022–2023 rules |
| WCO HS6 descriptions | `nli/data/raw/` | Input to TSI classifier |
| TSI labels (final) | `nli/data/processed/tsi_final.csv` | **Used by all three chapters** |
| Network edge lists | `networks/data/raw/` | Filtered from BACI |
| Regression-ready panels | `econometrics/data/processed/` | Output of concordance scripts |

### The flow: raw → interim → processed

```
data/raw/          ← original files, never touched
    ↓
data/interim/      ← cleaning and concordance scripts write here
    ↓
data/processed/    ← final analysis-ready files notebooks read from
```

### Data is not in Git

All `data/` folders are blocked by `.gitignore`. Share data via the project shared drive — never commit CSV, parquet, or Excel files to the repo. GitHub has a 100 MB file limit and large files will break the repo for everyone.

---

## 8. Chapter overview

### NLI — TSI classifier (do this first)

Produces `tsi_final.csv` which all other chapters depend on.

- Input: WCO HS6 official descriptions (`nli/data/raw/`)
- Method: zero-shot NLI using Qwen3-Embedding over five TSI stage hypotheses
- Output: `nli/data/processed/tsi_final.csv` — columns: `hs6 | tsi_stage | entropy | main_spec`
- Validation: BEC confusion matrix (`nli/outputs/tsi_labels/bec_confusion_matrix.xlsx`)

### Econometrics — stage-selective decoupling

Tests whether US–China tariff effects differed across TSI stages S1–S5.

- Input: BACI bilateral flows + Section 301 tariff lists + `tsi_final.csv`
- Method: TWFE regression with stage × tariff interactions, event-study design
- Output: regression tables in `econometrics/outputs/tables/`

### Networks — semiconductor trade network

Maps the bilateral trade network by stage, tracks China's centrality pre/post tariffs.

- Input: BACI bilateral flows + `tsi_final.csv`
- Method: NetworkX directed weighted graphs, betweenness centrality, stage-layer views
- Output: network figures in `networks/outputs/figures/`

---

## 9. Notebook naming convention

All notebooks and R scripts follow this format:

```
[number]-[initials]-[description].ipynb   (Python)
[number]-[initials]-[description].Rmd     (R)
```

Examples:

```
01-ae-tsi-classifier-validation.ipynb
02-ae-baci-extract-semiconductor-universe.ipynb
01-ae-baseline-regression.Rmd
01-ae-network-construction.ipynb
```

- Number keeps files in logical order within each chapter folder
- Initials prevent naming clashes when multiple people work in the same folder
- Description is lowercase, hyphen-separated, under 40 characters

> **Clear all cell outputs before committing.** Python: `Ctrl/Cmd+Shift+P` → "Jupyter: Clear All Outputs". R: `Session → Restart R and Clear Output`. Large output diffs make code review impossible.

